## Implementation Overview

The implementation was executed in a **controlled manner** using a fixed corpus (**335 words, narrative style**) and a fixed query set of **35 questions**, with cosine similarity threshold set at **0.75** and only **Top-1 chunk** passed to the LLM for generation.

In the **baseline setup (Phase 1 — Chunk 50, Nomic embeddings)**, the system produced **17 positive retrievals** and **18 negatives**. After reclassification based on generation correctness, the final distribution was **11 True Positives**, **6 False Positives**, **13 True Negatives**, and **5 False Negatives**, indicating **30% effective success rate (11/35)**.  
Geometrically, the space showed **low embedding variance (0.0003)** and **high inter-chunk similarity (~0.735)**, indicating a **tightly clustered and ambiguous embedding space**.

In **Phase 2 — Cross Corpus Comparison**, it was observed that retrieval performance is influenced by **representation style**. While rule-based and Q&A corpora showed better separation (**higher rank gaps ~0.10**), they also exhibited **higher False Positives** due to insufficient answer completeness despite high similarity. This established that **separation alone does not guarantee correct retrieval outcomes**.

In **Phase 3 — Retrieval Optimization**, re-ranking provided **limited improvements**, converting only a few False Positives into True Positives and showing **no benefit in cases where knowledge was absent**.  
Re-chunking the narrative corpus from **50 to 75 words** significantly improved performance, increasing **True Positives from 11 to 15** and reducing **False Positives from 6 to 2**, improving the effective success rate from **30% to 42%**. Further increase to **100 words** showed **marginal gains**, confirming that **75 words provided the optimal balance between context and dilution**.

Geometrically, re-chunking resulted in **reduced embedding variance (0.000307 → 0.000253 → 0.000237)** due to semantic averaging, **increased inter-chunk similarity (0.7349 → 0.7668 → 0.7729)**, and **increased rank gap (0.0416 → 0.0614 → 0.0698)** due to reduced competition among chunks.

In **Phase 4 — Contrastive Learning**, the approach was applied selectively to **5 cases (4 False Negatives + 1 False Positive)**. After iterative training, all **4 False Negatives were converted to True Positives**, increasing True Positives from **15 to 19** and improving overall success rate to **54% (19/35)**.  
**False Positives remained unchanged**, confirming that **contrastive learning improves retrieval separation but does not address knowledge absence or gating limitations**.

The geometric impact of contrastive learning was significant, with **embedding variance increasing (0.000253 → 0.001370)** and **inter-chunk similarity reducing sharply (0.7668 → 0.3685)**, indicating **improved spread and separation**. Rank gap for HIGH band appeared as **zero due to threshold classification effects**, not due to loss of separation.

It is important to note that contrastive learning required a transition from **Nomic embeddings to a fine-tuned SentenceTransformer model**, resulting in a **change in vector space**. Therefore, geometric metrics are **interpreted directionally rather than numerically across models**.

A key observation from the implementation is that **similarity-based gating has inherent limitations**. In the False Positive case (**Q35**), the system triggered generation due to **high similarity**, but the retrieved chunk lacked **sufficient answerable content**. The LLM correctly returned **“insufficient information”**, demonstrating that **high similarity does not imply answer completeness**.  
This confirms that the limitation lies in the **gating mechanism**, not in the **retriever or the LLM**.

Overall, the implementation shows that retrieval improvements were achieved in two stages—first through **representation tuning (re-chunking)** and then through **geometry shaping (contrastive learning)**—while final system behavior remains dependent on the **interaction between retrieval, generation, and gating mechanisms**.
